definition.value: A hydrazone resulting from the formal condensation of an aldehyde or ketone with the non-acylated nitrogen of semicarbazide or its substituted derivatives.
An organonitrogen heterocyclic antibiotic containing a quinolone (or quinolone-like) moiety and which have a fluorine atom attached to the central ring system.
An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo groups of 7-phenyl-5-[(4-sulfophenyl)imino]-5,7-dihydrobenzo[a]phenazine-3-sulfonic acid.

An organic heterotetracyclic compound that is 7-phenyl-5-imino-5,7-dihydrobenzo[a]phenazine-3-sulfonic acid in which the imino hydrogen is replaced by a 4-sulfophenyl group. The monosodium salt is the biological stain 'azocarmine G'.
An organic sodium salt that is the disodium salt of 4-[(7-phenyl-3-sulfobenzo[a]phenazin-7-ium-5-yl)amino]benzene-1,3-disulfonic acid.
An N-terminal alpha-amino-acid residue derived from 5-oxo-L-proline.
An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo groups of 4-[(7-phenyl-3-sulfobenzo[a]phenazin-5-ylidene)amino]benzene-1,3-disulfonic acid.

An organic heterotetracyclic compound that is 7-phenyl-5-imino-5,7-dihydrobenzo[a]phenazine-3-sulfonic acid in which the imino hydrogen is replaced by a 2,4-disulfophenyl group. The disodium salt is the biological stain 'azocarmine B'.
An organic sodium salt that is the disodium salt of 5,7-dinitro-8-hydroxynaphthalene-2-sulfonic acid.
An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo and phenolic hydroxy groups of flavianic acid.

A naphthalenesulfonic acid that is naphthalene-2-sulfonic acid substituted by nitro groups at positions 5 and 7 as well as a hydroxy group at position 8. The disodium salt is the biological stain 'naphthol yellow S'.
A diglyceride in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 40 carbons and 4 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as icosanoyl (arachidoyl) and arachidonoyl respectively.
A diglyceride in which the acyl groups contain a total of 40 carbons and 5 double bonds.
A diacylglycerol 40:5 in which the acyl groups specified are  icosanoyl and (5Z,8Z,11ZZ,14Z,17Z)-eicosapentaenoyl respectively,

An organic sodium salt having  6-amino-2-(4-methylphenyl)-1,3-dioxo-2,3-dihydro-1H-benzo[de]isoquinoline-5-sulfonate as the counterion. It is used as the displacement dye in the yellowsolve I method for fibrin.
A diglyceride in which the acyl groups contain a total of 40 carbons and 8 double bonds.
A class of sulfonamides whose members generally have bacteriostatic antibiotic properties.
A member of the class of furans in which the furan ring is substituted by a nitro group and which also has significant antibiotic properties.
An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo group of lissamine flavine FF.
A diglyceride in which the acyl groups contain a total of 38 carbons and 0 double bonds.

A member of the class of benzoisoquinolines that is 1,3-dioxo-2,3-dihydro-1H-benzo[de]isoquinoline-5-sulfonic acid substituted by 4-tolyl and amino groups at positions 2 and 6 respectively. The monosodium salt is the biological stain 'lissamine flavine FF'.
A diacylglycerol 38:0 in which the acyl groups specified at positions 1 and 2 are hexadecanoyl and docosanoyl respectively.

An organic sodium salt having 3-[(4-anilinophenyl)diazenyl]benzene-1-sulfonate as the counterion. Used in one variant of Masson's trichrome to stain collagen yellow in contrast to the red muscle, but is not in common used.

A hydrochloride salt resulting from the formal reaction of 3-[(3-chlorophenoxy)methyl]-1-(tetrahydro-2H-pyran-4-yl)-1H-pyrazolo[3,4-d]pyrimidin-4-amine with 2 mol eq. of hydrogen chloride. It is a selective inhibitor of the delta- and epsilon-isoforms of casein kinase 1 (CK1delta and CK1epsilon).

A pyrazolopyrimidine that is 1H-pyrazolo[3,4-d]pyrimidin-4-amine which is substituted at positions 1 and 3 by tetrahydro-2H-pyran-4-yl and (m-chlorophenoxy)methyl groups, respectively. It is a selective inhibitor of the epsilon isoform of casein kinase 1 (CK1epsilon).
An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo group of 3-[(4-anilinophenyl)diazenyl]benzene-1-sulfonic acid.
A diglyceride in which the acyl groups  contain a total of 40 carbons and 0 double bonds.

A member of the class of azobenzenes that is azobenzene in which one of the phenyl groups is substituted at the para position by an anilino group, while the other is substituted at a meta position by a sulfo group. The monosodium salt is the biological stain 'metanil yellow'.
A diacylglycerol 40:0 in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are octadecanoyl and docosanoyl respectively.
A member of the class of lipid As that is lipid A in which the free OH group on the N-hydroxytetradecanoyl group is carrying a palimitoyl group.
A diglyceride in which the acyl groups contain a total of 40 carbon atoms and 0 double bonds.
A member of the class of lipid As that is lipid IVA in which one of the free OH groups on the two N-hydroxytetradecanoyl groups is carrying a palimitoyl group.
A member of the class of lipid As that is lipid IIA in which one of the free OH groups on the two N-hydroxytetradecanoyl groups is carrying a palimitoyl group.
A diacylglycerol 40:10 in which the acyl groups specified at positions 1 and 2 are (6Z,9Z,12Z,15Z)-octadecatetraenoyl and (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoyl respectively.
A gallate ester obtained by the formal condensation of gallic acid with ethanol.
A beta-D-glucosiduronic acid that is the ethyl derivative of beta-D-glucuronic acid.
A monoglyceride in which the acyl contains a total of 14 carbon atoms and 0 double bonds.
A monoglyceride in which the acyl group contains a total of 16 carbon atoms and 0 double bond.
A monoglyceride in which the acyl group contains a total of 16 carbon atoms and 1 double bond.
A monoacylglycerol 16:1 in which the acyl group specified at position 2 is 9Z)-hexadecenoyl.
A monoglyceride in which the acyl group contains a total of 18 carbon atoms and 0 double bonds.
A monoglyceride in which the acyl group contains a total of 18 carbon atoms and 1 double bond.
A monoglyceride in which the acyl groups contain a total of 18 carbons and two double bonds.
A monoglyceride in which the acyl group contains a total of 18 carbon atoms and 3 double bonds.
An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (E)-2-methylpentadec-2-enoic acid.
An O-glycosyl-L-serine having N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine as the glycosyl component.
An O-glycosyl-L-threonine having N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine as the glycosyl component.
An o-quinone resulting from the formal oxidation of the dihydroxyphenyl moiety of 2-hydroxyestrone.
An o-quinone resulting from the formal oxidation of the dihydroxyphenyl moiety of 4-hydroxyestrone.
